The model demonstrates a significant overall similarity within its standard deviation. The notable increase in diagnosed cases in the last ten days could be attributed to the rise in testing in Peru. Alternatively, it could be linked to the consistent decrease in isolation levels in the country, which have been below 50% for most days in the past month. We have assumed a fixed isolation level based on the early days following government decrees in Peru. However, data from the same source indicates that these levels are subject to change. As a result, the number of diagnosed cases and deaths in future simulations may exceed those reported in this paper (refer to the "keep isolation" scenario in the following section).

In terms of daily death toll, the average number projected by our models is higher than the official figures. This discrepancy is expected due to potential underdetection rates exacerbated by a lower number of tests being conducted. To further explore this issue, we examined the number of deaths in Peru from January 1 to April 30, comparing data from 2019 and 2020; the findings are illustrated in Figure 5. A clear upward trend is evident after February 26, the date of Peru's first confirmed case of COVID-19, suggesting that the actual death toll may be significantly higher than reported figures.

Looking ahead, we have identified four potential actions to be considered after 90 days (May 26) following the initial phase of the epidemic:
a) Maintain current isolation levels without any additional measures;
b) End isolation and resume normal activities, restoring initial network layers and weights;
c) Resume only work-related activities, reinstating the initial layer's probability;
d) Enhance isolation by halting all remaining work and transport activities.
